headline: Elizabeth Warren grilled over claims of Native American heritage
subHeadline: Sen. Warren struggles to answer questions about ancestry; reaction and analysis on 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everyone. I'm Dana Perino along with Martha MacCallum, Juan Williams, Jesse Watters, and Greg Gutfeld. It's 5 o'clock in New York City, and this is “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Shut up about politics. Ain't nothing but a big pile of dirty tricks. I'm tired of all the fighting and the [EXPLETIVE] fits, so shut up --

utterances.speaker: THE FIVE HOSTS
utterances.sentences: Shut up.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: -- about politics. You punch left, I punch right. We're caught up in the middle of a deep swamp fight. Some people lie, some people steal, but everybody's talking about the green new deal,

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: So it's a pretty amazing moment for us here at “The Five,” after John Rich performed our song, shut up about politics on the show yesterday. It reached number one on the iTunes country chart, and number two overall on iTunes. Remember, if you haven't downloaded it, it's available on all music platform with all proceed, all of it, going to Folds of Honor which provides scholarship for children and spouses of our fallen and disable service members. It's only 99 cent, Greg. It's not even a dollar. So, that's pretty fun.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, HOST
utterances.sentences: Yeah, but I don't want to be a downer. I have second thoughts about the charity.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Don't be a downer.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I mean, I didn't think it was going to be this successful. I mean, if we told them 80 percent, they wouldn't have known the 20 percent - - I mean, there's a lot of money. If we've said -- if we say we're going to give 80 percent to charity, there would be -- you know what? You guys are really awesome. But no, we had to go 100 percent.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.sentences: What kind of money are we looking at? I just want to know --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No, no, if you haven't done --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: What money are we missing out on?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Why do you think the song was so successful that quickly?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Call and response is always good. With shut up about you get people to say shut up, it's potent. If you have a jukebox in a bar because everybody in the bar gets involved. Also it's economical, it's about 2 minutes and 20 seconds long. I can say it's a punk rock song. It's not like some progressive moody blues dirt --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Do not compare this to punk rock.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. And it's got a great concept, shut up about politics, which is what, you know -- I came up with a list for the entire album, shut up about sports.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: OK.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Shut up about your healthy diet. Shut up about your vacation. Shut up about your pets, nothing personal. Shut up about the weather, and then shut up about shutting up.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Also shut up about your travel woes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes, exactly.

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, HOST
utterances.sentences: Why don't we just say shut up?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You know, Gregory and I often go back and forth, so I have a different view about the success of this song, Gregory, and here it is.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: What?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: We've got a great audience. The audience, really, is supporting us. And I think that they have made a decision here -- hey, “The Five” is a lot of fun. We had fun with “The Five.” And so they're part of the team.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: We should probably give some credit to John Rich who is a mega- superstar.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: But, Juan, I would agree with you, the song is successful despite you not being in it. Kind of like the show being successful despite you being in it. But you know -- what?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: What?

utterances.speaker: MARTHA MACCALLUM, HOST
utterances.sentences: I think you would have benefitted from having Juan yelling shut up --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't know. I'm kind of glad Juan wasn't there for it. I think Juan's deep baritone would have ruined the pitch.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Why? Because you think that your voice stands out?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Mine carries that voice.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: That's what it's about.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Martha, what do you think?

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: I watched you guys, you know, when you're recording it. And in the beginning everyone was little timid. It was like shut up. And then it was like, come on. And you were yelling and it got, you know, a lot stronger and better and I think that's why it such a big hit. Everybody wants people to shut up about politics and stuff.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: If we only get one ticket to the Grammys, I'm going.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The CMA's.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: The CMA's also -- that would be more fun.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: Wow.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, that's true.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Now, Donna Brazile was there with us, and I think she -- she called in just for a quick moment. Donna, are you there?

utterances.speaker: DONNA BRAZILE, CONTRIBUTOR
utterances.sentences: I'm here. Let me just say this. Juan, first of all, thank you for taking that day off --

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.sentences: I've had such a great time. Not only did I provide the mood, I provided the groove. I was (INAUDIBLE). And I was Santa's background. We were like the Supremes with two temptations.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: My Louisiana sister definitely knows good music.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.sentences: Oh, my God, I had a great time. I downloaded it. My family downloaded it. That's why it's number one because it was so much fun. I can't wait to do another song with you all. But, Greg, if you go to the Grammys without me, you know --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I make sure you get to the after-party.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.sentences: Please.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Donna Brazile, you're a big reason it went to number one. Thank you. We'll talk to you soon.

utterances.speaker: BRAZILE
utterances.sentences: See you soon, bye-bye.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: See, I was a little embarrassed because someone who I know is in the country music industry, and I got a text saying congratulations on your number one song on the country charts, and they've been working their entire career to get number one.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Is that Taylor? This is Taylor so upset, yet she called me --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes, Taylor.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: She called me. She was upset when we broke up in 2010. This is just salt on the wound.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: She wrote a song about that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I have to say Blake Shelton -- he's got to be wondering, wow, where this come from?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You better watch your back.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: This is grassroots. This is the fans. We have a little bit of a treat because our producers put together a song -- a music video, the first “Five” music video for you to watch and listen to. Here we go.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Shut up, shut up, about politics. Ain't nothing but a big pile of dirty tricks. I'm tired of all the fighting and the [EXPLETIVE] fits, so shut up, shut up, about politics. You punch left, I punch right. We're caught up in the middle of a deep swamp fight. Some people lie, some people steal, and everybody's talking about the green new deal. I'm tired of all the fighting and the [EXPLETIVE] fits, so shut up, shut up, about politics Shut up, shut up, about politics. Shut up, shut up, about politics.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: There you go. You've got to hear it in full because they have the full band. He only gave you a little taste of it yesterday. But I'm sure you downloaded it. If you haven't, you can do that anywhere --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I have a question. I saw my friend Jesse Watters grabbing my friend Greg Gutfeld around the waist.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yeah, that was kind of a weird -- what was going on there?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't know what that was. I was tickling you. I'm trying to pick you up.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh, no.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I'm embarrassed by that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: All I know I had a long discussion with H.R.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I'm a touchy-feely guy like the vice president.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: At least you have a record of it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, that's right. Video evidence.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Exactly.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I'm going to need to see that footage after the show.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: There's no question. We should thank John Rich and your band and the whole production team, Jewels who helps with the promotion. We appreciate it. We're very excited. Keep this thing going because it all goes -- all the proceeds go to Folds of Honor.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: All of it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right, switching gears, Chicago police released a throve of documents related to the Jussie Smollett case, all the details when we return.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: So a new development in the Jussie Smollett case today, Chicago police had released hundreds of document related to the alleged hate crime hoax by the former Empire actor. Among the revelations, prosecutors told detectives that they were working on a possible plea deal with Smollett a month before all 16 felony count against him were suddenly dropped.  The files also shows Smollett denied to police that the brothers linked to the case were his attackers citing their dark skin color because he said that his attackers were white. And texts revealed that Smollett asked the brothers if they have contacts at one point. There's -- this text messages between them looking for ecstasy or cocaine months before the allege attacks, so clearly he was very familiar with both of them at that point. So, you know, this is not going away. And this is very bad news for Kim Foxx who was the prosecutor who dropped this case to everyone's shock. Greg, you know, this is very interesting to me that this is like people have dug their teeth in, and I think it's very good news for equal justice.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know what it is? I do think that they under-estimated the magnitude of the hoax. They looked at past hoaxes and generally the media will cover the incident. But when the incident unravels they tend move on. But because this had taken a national -- the size of a national story because of the MAGA hats and the Trump relationship, it made hiding this impossible. So once it was unraveling they were -- I think they were trying to do him a favor and sweep this under the rug. Just a community service, pay a fine. And what happen was he couldn't keep his mouth shut. He couldn't keep his end of the deal and he screwed himself. I do have -- I've said this before, he can resurrect his career and make his life better to come clean and actually directly appeal to the people that he demonized. You know, there is a potential -- especially -- You know, among Republicans and conservative and the religious, do not underestimate the amount of forgiveness that is out there. If he was to say, look, I wrongly smeared, you know -- like that would be something that I would listen to.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, it's all about Trump.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Watch him on television.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No, I'm talking about forgive -- like, he could come clean --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, it's not conservatives. It's Trump backers because of the MAGA hats, that's what you're saying.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No, no, no, it's not about --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, because I don't think it's conservatives. I don't think that it's people who are Republican --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You're missing my point. I'm talking about a chance to be -- a chance for a guy to actually do something right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, you know, this thing is so confusing. It's a big mess in my mind.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But I will say this, I think the guy lied. I don't think there's much doubt about it. But I was surprised this morning in terms of this dump, Martha, because I didn't think there was much news here. I don't think there's much news there. It seems to me to be a situation where cops see things differently than prosecutors. The cops see that something happen here. They think he lied, as I do. The prosecutor said, you know what, this isn't worth the time, the money and the effort to prosecute this guy. He's some big star. He's unlikely to ever do anything like this again or commit any violent crime. Let's make a deal and get out of here. But some people -- and I think it's because of the politics behind it, don't want to let it go.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Juan, there was new information there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He was behind it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: There was no information. We didn't know he had a previous conviction, that was new.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, sure we knew that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No, we did not. We did not know that. We also didn't know there was this drug connection between him and the brothers.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, come on.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: We also didn't know -- only through leaks, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, OK.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: We also didn't know of the fact that he was offered to pick these two out of a line-up and he refused. And we didn't know either that the sweetheart deal was in the process of becoming a sweetheart deal from earlier on than we thought. So the whole thing was crooked from the jump. And like Greg had said before, we dodged a race war. If you have seen the video of two guys in MAGA hats beating a celebrity black gay actor on the street of Chicago, this would have been like wild fire. And there would have been violence across the country base off of the hoax.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, get out of here.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Are you kidding me? Jussie Smollett, you think he's Dr. King now?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Juan --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Come on man.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Juan, he's a black actor who's a homosexual --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: They have an actual video of MAGA hats --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I've never heard of the guy before this.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: Yeah. But let's also remember that celebrities all came out in support of him, many of them came out and supported him. It was a cause celeb, and it was very embarrassing for all of them when suddenly it turns out that the story is not what everybody thought it was. I mean, he did very high-profile interviews with Robin Roberts. He was, you know, so worked up about these guys. He said I want that video found so badly so that everyone can stop saying that this is an alleged attack. People do not --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That was the best acting he ever did.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: Yeah, exactly, right? I think the color is irrelevant here --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, come on. This is about -- look, this is about what Greg said. It's about --

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: It's about right and wrong. You don't makeup stuff.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, come on. The police thought on the bus --

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: They sure did.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: The police shoots themselves in front of the bus. The police chief ran in front of the bus with the mayor and cite, oh, yeah, yeah, we know this, we know that. You know what? They should have waited. You should not persecute in the name of prosecute.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Sounds like Robert Mueller.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: He did smeared the police. He also smeared the brothers. And now that you have the situation where the city is out of the money for the investigations that went forward, and he got away with only paying the $10,000. If he had kept his mouth shut, his show might still be going on. Remember, because all of the actors really wants the show to continue, but because it became -- got so far out of control they couldn't do that. But now these -- the brothers are having to sue him -- the lawyers, Smollett's lawyers because they can't figure out a way to make a living. So he's like basically -- like there's a trail of destruction behind this guy, and that's why --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The brothers wants to work for Watters' World. There's two slots open --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- as producers. You're welcome.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Don't sell coke and ecstasy anymore.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: OK, never mind.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I'm just going along with your bad jokes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Say no to drugs, kids.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: And tell the truth. Just tell the truth.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Tell the truth.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: It's not that hard. Tell the truth. More trouble for Elizabeth Warren as she called out -- she's called out for faking her Native-American ancestry, faking is a theme tonight.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: You're kind of like the original Rachel Dolezal a little bit.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, man.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: You have to see this video after this.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Liz Warren ancestry debacle just keeps on getting worst. Check out the latest cringe-worthy moment as the 2020 Democrat gets grilled about her Native-American heritage.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: There was some reports that said you were a Native- American on your text and ball license, and she said you're Native-American on documents when you were a professor at Harvard. Like why did you do that?

utterances.speaker: SEN. ELIZABETH WARREN, D-MASS
utterances.sentences: So it's what I believe. You know that's -- like I said, what I learned from my family.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: When did you find out you weren't?

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.sentences: Well, it's -- I'm not a person of color. I'm not a citizen of a tribe.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Was there any benefit to that?

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.sentences: No. Boston Globe did a full investigation. It never affected -- nothing about my family ever affected any job I ever got.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: Did you get a discount in college?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: You're kind of like the original Rachel Dolezal a little bit. Rachel Dolezal was a white woman pretending to be black.

utterances.speaker: WARREN
utterances.sentences: This is what I learned from my family.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, God. Martha? That was awkward.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: So painful. He also said in another part, so your family told you were Native-American? He's looking at her. She's sitting there looking like Elizabeth Warren and she goes, yeah.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, God.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: It's just -- how long did you hold on to that? Well, you know, I just -- it is just so bizarre. If people just see through this stuff. You know, all anybody wants, and it goes from the last segment to here, is for people to be authentic, right?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: And I know -- you know, everyone talks about the president, he is -- you know, many people say is a big liar. Some people -- you know, even the kind people say he's an exaggerator, right? There's that something that is authentic about him whether you love him or you hate him. And so, this kind of stuff just smacks of that totally uncomfortable feeling when you feel like somebody is trying to -- you know, be sort of like part of a protected class and they're not. It's --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And what made it even --

utterances.speaker: MACCALLUM
utterances.sentences: It doesn't feel good.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- more powerful is because this isn't a professional media interview. This is a relaxed group of guys on the radio that speak like regular people. And she can get away with her dances and her talking points if you do something on a network, but you can't speak honestly about what you did because you lied and it comes across so obvious.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, one, Charlemagne, the guy, is not just any interviewer. I mean, he's terrific. I mean, that show is a big hit --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, but he's casual and disarming, and she's -- won't be able to handle that.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Maybe they're not dress up for TV, but I don't think they're casual disarming. All the Democrats want to get on that show right now. I'll tell you why --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I'm trying to say he did a good interview --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I think he did a terrific interview.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- and spoke like a regular guy.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yeah. But I think he got to the heart and soul of the matter. You look at the questions it's almost bullet point fashion, you know, like, hey, we think you have deceived us. And so, that's an important point. Now to the politics of it, it doesn't matter. I don't think that anybody who's going to vote for Elizabeth Warren is gonna say, oh, I'm now not going to vote for Elizabeth Warren. If Elizabeth Warren gets the Democratic nomination and President Trump begins calling her Pocahontas, do you think that's any different that if any of the other 23 get the nomination or is he going --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I think, Dana, if you're listening and you're, you know, listener to --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- and you hear this and there's a primary coming up --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: In the last day or two, Politico had an article showing that Elizabeth Warren had sort of gaining with African-American voters, and she's in a fight against Bernie Sanders for second place. And, yeah, I think all of this matters if you have 24 candidates and people are shopping around. She's the only one that put forward very detailed policy proponents. But this is always been about affirmative action. She's a white woman who listed herself as a Native-American to try to get some sort of boost in her career, in her Ivy League application, and when we know that that happen because we know that the university then utilize it for her. And she has tried to figure out a way to overcome it. I don't think she's expected it today?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Because it was -- she's uncomfortable because it's uncomfortable to watch it and to know about it. The one thing is -- Donald Trump can call her Pocahontas and it's like -- his face laugh, but when it's coming from somebody else, when it's coming from -- maybe someone who might be on your left or on the Democratic side, that is a different thing. And I wonder if somebody like a Kamala Harris or a Cory Booker or even Bernie Sanders that wants to try to figure out a way to get a leg up will actually use this against her.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, do you think that would happen in the debate?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I think that this is allowing that to happen. Specifically, I think that Charlemagne did this because he has, you know, he has an allegiance to another candidate. And he also, obviously, watches THE FIVE because in October 2018, we gave Elizabeth Warren the Rachel Dolezal award in my monologue. So thank you, Charlemagne. Also, he's like a laser beam. Like, I don't think I want to be interviewed by him because he just -- like, he listen to her spiel, her patronizing spiel about all of these redistributionists policies, and he just kind of waited and waited and he just -- one by one, kicked back the most common sense question and it was just like -- that what made it painful because it was so on the level and persistent. You could argue that it helps her in the sense that no one hits her for her policies.
